\pard\qc\fs22\b 1 INTRODUCTION\par
\pard\fs18 1.1 General (Introduction to Project)\par
This project implements a compact, single-host telemetry and anomaly-detection system for Windows workstations. It includes a Python-based collector capturing keystrokes, mouse events, active-application context, and system metrics; a MySQL database storing raw and processed events; and a Java Swing UI that visualizes live data and performs scheduled processing to normalize logs into domain tables and raise alerts. The system uses a Rust hasher for payload integrity with a Python SHA-256 fallback and favors JDBC for reliable low-latency persistence.\par
\par
1.2 Motivation\par
- Provide near-real-time visibility into workstation behavior for rapid detection of anomalies.\par
- Deliver a lightweight, easy-to-deploy single-host solution compared to heavyweight enterprise agents.\par
- Combine native Rust performance for hashing with JDBC reliability for storage.\par
\par
1.3 Objectives\par
- Continuously capture keystrokes, mouse, app context, and system metrics while logging is enabled.\par
- Persist events to MySQL with JDBC; maintain median insert latency under typical local load.\par
- Refresh UI at ~1 Hz and show newest-1000 rows per table.\par
- Run an in-UI processor every 5s to populate domain tables and insert alerts.\par
- Allow one-click CSV export of any table.\par
\par
1.4 Scope\par
- Single Windows host, local MySQL instance; no distributed ingestion.\par
- Heuristic anomaly detection; no heavy ML model included by default.\par
- Privacy-conscious defaults: hashed payloads and optional raw_data retention.\par
\par
1.5 Sustainable Development Goal of the Project\par
- SDG 9 (Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure): improves resilient infrastructure for monitoring.\par
- SDG 16 (Peace, Justice and Strong Institutions): supports accountable logging and incident detection.\par
\page

\pard\qc\fs22\b 2 SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS\par
\pard\fs18 Summary:\par
Minimum: Windows 10/11 (64-bit), Python 3.10+, JDK 11+, MySQL 8.x, 4 GB RAM, 10 GB free disk. Recommended: 8 GB RAM, SSD, JDK 17, Python 3.11, local MySQL with 1+ GB free DB space.\par
\par
2.1 Hardware Requirements\par
Minimum:\par
- CPU: Dual-core 2 GHz\par
- RAM: 4 GB\par
- Disk: 10 GB free\par
Recommended:\par
- CPU: Quad-core 2.5 GHz\par
- RAM: 8+ GB\par
- Disk: SSD 20+ GB free\par
\par
2.2 Software Requirements\par
- OS: Windows 10/11 (64-bit)\par
- Java: JDK 11 or newer (JDK 16+ recommended)\par
- MySQL Server 8.x (local)\par
- Python 3.10+ in virtualenv (packages: psutil, pynput, mysql-connector-python, jpype1, jaydebeapi, pywin32)\par
- MySQL Connector/J jar in `java/lib`; JFreeChart in `java/lib` for charts\par
- Rust toolchain (optional) to build the `rust_hasher` binary\par
\page

\pard\qc\fs22\b 3 SYSTEM DESIGN\par
\pard\fs18 3.1 System architecture diagram\par
Architecture: Single-host, three-layer design: Data Collector (Python) → Storage (MySQL) ←→ Presentation/Processor (Java UI). Collector hashes payloads via Rust hasher and writes to MySQL via JDBC (or python connector fallback). UI reads via JDBC and processes logs every 5s to normalize domain tables and create alerts.\par
\par
ASCII diagram:\par
User\par
  ↓\par
[Java Swing UI] ←→ (JDBC) ←→ [MySQL Database]\par
  ↓ spawn\par
[Python Logger] → (Rust Hasher → fallback SHA256) → (JDBC / mysql-connector) → [MySQL Database]\par
(UI Processor every 5s → domain tables + alerts)\par
\par
3.2 Use case diagram\par
- User: Start/Stop logging, view live data, export CSV, review alerts.\par
- Python Logger: captures events and writes to DB.\par
- UI Processor: runs scheduled normalization and alerting.\par
\par
3.3 Class diagram (textual)\par
Java classes:\par
- BehaviorLoggerUI: main window, spawn logger, realtime updates, processLogsInUI()\par
- BehaviorLoggerUIMain: launcher and terminal integration\par
- DBUtils: helper functions for JDBC (suggested)\par
Python modules:\par
- behavior_log.py: capture & insert, hashing via rust_hasher\par
- realtime_processor.py / simple_processor.py: optional background normalization\par
\page

\pard\qc\fs22\b 4 MODULE DESCRIPTION\par
\pard\fs18 4.1 Module 1 — Event Collector (Python)\par
Purpose: Capture keyboard, mouse, application, and system metrics; hash payloads; insert into `behavior_logs`.\par
Key functions:\par
- log_event(event_type, data): hash with Rust hasher; insert via JDBC or mysql-connector\par
- setup_database(): create `behavior_logs` if missing\par
Inputs: keyboard/mouse hooks, active window/process info, psutil metrics\par
Dependencies: Rust hasher (binary), JPype/jaydebeapi for JDBC (optional), mysql-connector-python fallback\par
\par
4.2 Module 2 — Java UI & Processor\par
Purpose: Display live data, chart events/sec, spawn Python logger, run in-UI processor to create domain tables and alerts.\par
Key functions:\par
- startLogging(): launch Python logger from venv\par
- processLogsInUI(): read unprocessed rows, update prediction/processed_at, insert into domain tables and alerts\par
- updateAnalytics() and updateChartSeries() for visual summary\par
\par
4.3 Module 3 — Database Schema & Storage (MySQL)\par
Key tables: behavior_logs, behavior_events, keystroke_events, mouse_events, application_events, system_metrics, alerts, anomaly_stats\par
Notes: index `id` and `timestamp` for fast queries; be mindful of FK constraints when inserting normalized rows.\par
\par
4.4 Module 4 — Optional Processors / Utilities\par
- simple_processor.py / realtime_processor.py for daemonized normalization\par
- utilities: show_counts.py, inspect_tables.py for DB introspection\par
\par
4.5 Result\par
- Live UI with near-real-time inserts and charting\par
- Domain tables populated and alerts created for heuristics (e.g., high CPU or keystroke spikes)\par
- CSV export available for user data extraction\par
\page

